notesStmt.note: This illuminated copy of the Qur'an was produced in the eleventh century AH / seventeenth CE in Iran. Apart from using a number of scripts, such as naskh, muḥaqqaq, and tawqīʿ, the manuscript features six pairs of decorated pages; two illuminated headpieces; and chapter headings, interlinear illumination, and marginal decoration. The Qur'anic text begins on fol. 2b and ends on fol. 331a. It is followed by a prayer (duʿāʾ) and a table of divination (taf'ul) in Arabic and Persian (fols. 332b-333a).The black leather binding has a central piece in the form of a diamond with pendants on four sides. The inner boards, with their traditional dentelle decoration, feature text from the "verse of the throne" (āyat al-kursī), 2:255-6, which is inscribed in the outer frame.

msContents.textLang: The primary language in this manuscript is Arabic. The secondary language of this manuscript is Persian.

msItem.title: al-Qurʾān
القرآن
msItem.note: Text of Qur'an begins on fol. 2b and ends on fol. 331a, followed by a prayer (duʿāʾ) to be recited after the Qur'anic text and a table of divination (taf'ul) in Arabic and Persian (fols. 332b-333a)

layoutDesc.layout: Framing lines in green, orange, gold, black, sepia, and blue

handDesc.handNote: Written mainly in naskh script; muḥaqqaq script in center medallions on fols. 2b-3a, 152b-153a, and 331b-332a; tawqīʿ script for chapter headings and other incidental inscriptions

decoDesc.decoNote: Six pairs of decorated pages (fols. 1b-2a, 2b-3a, 152b-153a, 331b-332a, and 332b-333a); two illuminated headpieces (fols. 3b and 154a); illuminated chapter headings; interlinear illumination; decorated borders; polychrome framing lines; marginal decorations and verse markers

decoNote.title: Right side of an illuminated double-page frontispiece
Left side of a double-page illuminated frontispiece
Right side of a double-page opening inscribed with verses of chapter 1
decoNote.note: This is the right side of a double-page opening decoration containing the text of chapter 1 (Sūrat al-fātiḥah) inscribed in the center medallion in gold muḥaqqaq script on a blue background.

decoNote.title: Left side of a double-page opening inscribed with verses of chapter 1
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a double-page opening decoration containing the text of chapter 1 (Sūrat al-fātiḥah) inscribed in the center medallion in gold muḥaqqaq script on a blue background.

decoNote.title: Illuminated incipit page with headpiece
decoNote.note: This illuminated incipit page introduces chapter 2 (Sūrat al-baqarah).

decoNote.title: Illuminated page with verses from the end of chapter 17
decoNote.note: This illuminated page contains verses from the end of chapter 17 (Sūrat Banī Isrāʾīl) inscribed in the center medallion in white muḥaqqaq script.

decoNote.title: Decorated incipit page with headpiece introducing chapter 18
decoNote.note: This is a decorated incipit page with an illuminated headpiece introducing chapter 18 (Sūrat al-kahf).

decoNote.title: Right side of an illuminated finispiece with inscribed prayer
decoNote.note: This richly decorated page contains a prayer to be recited at the end of the Qur'anic text. The prayer is inscribed in the center medallion in white muḥaqqaq script.

decoNote.title: Right side of a double-page table of divination (bibliomancy or tafa'ul)
decoNote.note: This is the right side of a table of divination (bibliomancy or tafa'ul) executed in Arabic in tawqīʿ script and in Persian in nastaʿlīq script. The top inscription reads: fī al-tafa<ʾ>ul min kalām Allāh al-Majīd.

decoNote.title: Left side of a double-page table of divination (bibliomancy or tafa'ul)
decoNote.note: This is the left side of a table of divination (bibliomancy or tafa'ul) executed in Arabic in tawqīʿ script and in Persian in nastaʿlīq script.

binding.p: Black leather (with flap); upper board with a central piece in the form of a diamond with pendants on four sides; inner boards, with traditional dentelle decoration, feature text from the "verse of the throne" (āyat al-kursī), 2:255-6, inscribed in the outer frame

history.acquisition: Walters Art Museum, 1931, by Henry Walters bequest
